  "text": "Systemic administration of dopamine (DA) D 1 or D 2 receptor-antagonists induce in rats catalepsy (0gren and Fuxe, 1988), i.e. a state of postural immobility (akinesia) and muscular rigidity. The available evidence suggests that catalepsy mainly originates from a blockade of D 1 or D 2 receptors in the caudate-putamen (CP) or a decreased presynaptic DA activity in this structure, since intrastriatal infusions of DA-antagonists (Elliott et al., 1990 a; [CITATION_1] , 6-hydroxydopamine-lesions of the mesostriatal DA system or reserpine treatment produced catalepsy (see Schmidt etal., 1992 for review).",
